entry.title: Use fallback Picker anchor bounds if caret is outside focused window.
entry.content:
CL:5261480 adds logic to anchor the Picker view at the mouse cursor as a

fallback when the text caret bounds are not available (or empty).



There are also situations where caret bounds can be non-empty but still

invalid, e.g. Google docs places the "caret bounds" offscreen, far away

from the visible text location. In these cases, it's probably better to

just anchor the Picker at the mouse cursor rather than the bogus caret

bounds.



As a heuristic to handle these situations, add an extra condition to

anchor at the fallback cursor point when the caret bounds are not

contained in the current focused window.

entry.title: media/gpu: Migrate frame mappers to FrameResource
entry.content:
The frame mappers now use the FrameResource container in their main code

paths. Clients can still use VideoFrames as inputs. They are converted to

FrameResource internally with VideoFrameMapper::Map(VideoFrame...) in

video_frame_mapper.cc.



The new FrameResource map method was named MapFrame() to avoid a name

conflict with the VideoFrame Map() and let the compiler select the

correct method when a derived class is explicitly used.



Both FrameResource and VideoFrame inputs are mapped into unowned memory

VideoFrame objects. If it is desired to map into a FrameResource, a

VideoFrameResource can be constructed from the mapped frame.



This also contains a change to create a source set for

video_frame_resource and video_frame_utils. video_frame_resource needs

to be separate from //media/gpu/chromeos:common to allow it to be

depended on by //media/gpu:video_frame_mapper_common without creating a

circular dependency.

entry.title: Router evaluation for subresources in the no fetch handler case
entry.content:
Before this CL, in the renderer, registered routers are not evaluated if

there is no fetch handler in the service worker. This is critical and

introduces unexpected behavior for the static routing API, because

developer may only use static routing API, that doesn't guarantee the

fetch handler existence.



This CL add the new boolean field, `need_router_evaluate` to

ControllerServiceWorkerInfo mojo interface. The renderer side use this

field to decide whether it involves ServiceWorkerSubresourceLoader or

not.

- ProcessMitigationsTest.CheckWin10MsSignedPolicyAndDllLoadSuccess

- ProcessMitigationsTest.CheckWin10MsSignedPolicySuccess



Original change's description:

> Enable sandbox shims to work regardless of timing

>

> There are several limitations with the sandbox shims, root caused as

> chromium sometimes accessing the Windows heap before it is safe to do

> so, when OS code attempts to call NtCreateSection or NtMapViewOfSection

> during super-early process start-up.

>

> NtCreateSection - used to bypass CIG checks for binaries not signed by

> Microsoft by brokering the syscall.

>

> NtMapViewOfSection - used to listen to DLL loads in case we want to

> also shim those DLLs.

>

> This change adds early exits to the NtMapViewOfSection when these APIs

> are called before kernel32 is loaded, to avoid needing to use the heap

> while the process is in this super-early startup phase. There is not a

> great publicly documented API we can use earlier, as Windows public API

> is generally in kernel32, ntdll is mostly undocumented.

>

> It should be safe to wait this long, as kernel32.dll should get loaded

> before any other DLLs we try to shim at runtime.

>

> For NtCreateSection shim, we modify it to only use stack memory instead

> of heap memory. We did not apply the same approach as the

> NtMapViewOfSection shim because NtCreateSection is not called for every

> DLL load, so the approach to wait for kernel32 would mean the shims have

> to depend on each other, though they are not always applied at the same

> time.

>

> Modified CheckWin10MsSignedPolicySuccess test so it actually applies the

> shims used to load other DLLs on release build. Validated that this test

> fails with AppVerifier enabled without these changes and passes with the

> changes.

>

> Verified manually with a smoke test that we can run chromium under

> page heap, app verifier, and under the conditions from crbug.com/1519187

>

> Also verified manually that sbox integration tests fail under these

> conditions without the changes to the shims, and they pass with the

> shim changes.

entry.title: Introduce SimpleUrlPatternMatcher class for Compression Dictionary
entry.content:
This CL introduces a new network::SimpleUrlPatternMatcher class for

Compression Dictionary Transport. This class partially implements URL

Pattern spec [1] which is needed for Dictionary URL matching [2].



This class provides two methods.

- Static `Create()` method which creates a SimpleUrlPatternMatcher from

a constructor string and a base URL. If the constructor string is

invalid or it contains regexp group, this method returns an error.

- `Match()` method which executes the `test` method in the spec [3] with

the provided URL.



This CL also moves the URL canonicalization related logic from Blink

into //components/url_pattern/ which can be used both from

//services/network and from Blink. (Note: We already have

//third_party/liburlpattern. But we can't use url/url_util.h from

there.)



[1]: https://urlpattern.spec.whatwg.org/

[2]: https://www.ietf.org/archive/id/draft-ietf-httpbis-compression-dictionary-01.html#name-dictionary-url-matching

[3]: https://urlpattern.spec.whatwg.org/#dom-urlpattern-test

entry.title: [iOS] Add form input accessory view tap recognizer on creation
entry.content:
The call to get form input accessory view will cause it to be created

immediately. This CL changes the timing of adding the tap recognizer to

when the view is created, so that it's lazily loaded when it's actually

used, rather than at app startup, which saves ~50ms to the startup

latency on the iPhone 7 (according to Instruments).



Instruments measurements:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gyVFWPn2WDPIyi5zY1WFUjhsL2Z26RsUyHLNw87lIWE/edit?usp=sharing

entry.title: IDB: move more of IndexedDBFactory into IndexedDBBucketContext
entry.content:
This moves the rest the code that sets up and tears down IDB

implementation classes like IndexedDBBackingStore from

IndexedDBFactory to IndexedDBBucketContext. IOW, this makes

IndexedDBBucketContext the mojo endpoint for `window.indexedDB`

API calls like `open()` and `deleteDatabase()`.



This is necessary because IndexedDBFactory shouldn't be reaching

into bucket sequence classes, and also because the renderer

should talk directly to the bucket sequence thread instead of

making an additional stop on the factory thread. What remains in

IndexedDBFactory should be folded into IndexedDBContextImpl.



Notably, and perhaps treacherously: this affects the lifetime of

the IndexedDBBucketContext. Formerly it was created when an api

method like `open()` or `deleteDatabase()` was invoked, and

discarded if it was not in use for over 2 seconds. With this

change, it is created when the first receiver is bound and

destroyed when the last receiver is unbound. The backing store

is still destroyed when not in use for over two seconds (via

`IndexedDBBucketContext::ResetBackingStore()`).

entry.title: v4l2/stateless: Failure to queue buffer should not be fatal
entry.content:
The |output_queue_| and by extension, the ImageProcessor,

are not created until the first frame has received a surface.

In the creation of the surface a frame id is generated.

When an error occurs after the |output_queue_| is created

and before a compressed buffer is submitted the dtor

on the surface will try and enqueue the buffer associated

with the frame. This should not be a fatal error.
